"Shropshire, England","Coton Hall, Nordley, Alveley Parish, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Coton, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"1366–1420":"1366–1420","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1378–1400":"1378–1400","1398–1450":"1398–1450","1340–1402":"1340–1402","1340–1408":"1340–1408","about 1390":"about 1390","1402":"1402","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1366":"1366","1398":"1398","1420":"1420","1365":"1365","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England":"Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Coton Hall, Nordley, Alveley Parish, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Coton, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leigh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places (in at least sixteen counties, but especially Leigh in Lancashire) named either with the nominative case of Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’ (see   Lee  ) or with <i>lēage</i>, a late dative form of this word (see   Lye  ).","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 李, based on its Cantonese pronunciation. See   Li   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Leah","meanings":["English: variant of   Leigh  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 李 and 利, see   Li   1 and 3."]},{"name":"Lee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sang, Jae, Jong, Jung, Sung, Yong, Kyung, Seung, Dong, Kwang, Myung.","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a meadow or a patch of arable land, Middle English <i>lee</i>, <i>lea</i>, from Old English <i>lēa</i>, dative case (used after a preposition) of <i>lēah</i>, which originally meant ‘wood or glade’.","English: habitational name from any of the many places in England named with Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade’, including Lee in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Kent, and Shropshire, and Lea in Cheshire, Derbyshire, Herefordshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, and Wiltshire."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":16,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Leigh was born in 1366, in Coton, Shropshire, England, his father, John Leigh, was 26 and his mother, Ellen Corona, was 26. He married Johanna Burnell about 1390, in Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1420, in his hometown, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1366–1420":"136